The 2019 Ford F-150 is a full-size pickup truck that is available in three cab styles: regular, SuperCab (extended) and SuperCrew (crew cab). There are three bed lengths offered, depending on which cab style is chosen: a 6.5-foot bed, an 8-foot bed or a 5.5-foot bed. The F-150 is available in seven trim levels: XL, XLT, Lariat, King Ranch, Platinum, Limited and Raptor.

The base XL comes standard with 17-inch steel wheels, automatic headlights, trailer sway control, pre-wired trailer connections, manual mirrors and windows, vinyl flooring, air conditioning, a tilt-and-telescoping steering wheel, a driver information display, a 4.2-inch central display screen, Bluetooth, and a four-speaker radio with auxiliary jack. SuperCab and SuperCrew models receive 60/40-split folding rear seats and two additional speakers.

An optional 101A package adds power windows and locks (including the tailgate), power mirrors, remote keyless entry, cruise control, a bigger driver information screen, Ford's MyKey vehicle control feature, a 4.2-inch center screen, Sync voice controls, smartphone app integration, a USB port and a CD player. Other XL add-ons include chrome and sport appearance packages, the FX4 Off-Road package, side steps, a tailgate assist step, and a trailer towing package with Ford's Pro Trailer Backup Assist system.

The XLT trim includes the XL's 101A package along with alloy wheels, chrome bumpers and exterior trim, foglights, a keypad entry system, rear privacy glass, driver and passenger seat lumbar adjustments, and additional interior storage bins and pockets.

The midlevel Lariat trim is only offered on SuperCab and SuperCrew models. It adds a 2.7-liter EcoBoost V6, 18-inch wheels, keyless entry and ignition, power-folding mirrors, an 8-inch driver information screen with expanded capabilities, dual-zone automatic climate control, leather upholstery, heated and ventilated front seats, driver-seat memory settings, ambient lighting, a leather-wrapped steering wheel and a power-adjustable pedals.

Notable options for the Lariat include the 502A package, which adds LED headlights and foglights, automatic high beams, automatic wipers, a heated and power-adjustable steering wheel, front bucket seats, an 11-speaker stereo with HD radio, a navigation system and an upgraded version of Sync 3. Stand-alone options include lane keeping assist, adaptive cruise control with forward collision warning, an automated parallel parking system, a surround-view camera system and inflatable rear seat belts.

The King Ranch trim is only offered on the SuperCrew cab and builds on the Luxury 502A package with a Western styling theme inside and out and with the 5.0-liter V8 underhood. With a bit more conventional luxury equipment, the Platinum trim adds 20-inch wheels, power-deployable running boards and wood and aluminum interior trim. Essentially at the top of the range is the F-150 Limited, which comes with the turbocharged 3.5-liter engine, 22-inch wheels, upgraded leather upholstery in the front, unique styling details and many of the F-150's optional features as standard.

The off-road-oriented Raptor model is similarly equipped to the XLT with the 101A package but comes with a reinforced frame, a special four-wheel-drive system, a modified long-travel suspension, flared fenders, skid plates, 17-inch wheels with upgraded off-road tires, and a unique interior trim with leather and cloth upholstery. The Raptor is available in both SuperCab and SuperCrew cab styles, and it is powered by a high-output version of the turbocharged 3.5-liter engine. Options on the Raptor include the 801A package, which adds the same interior upgrades as the XLT's Luxury 302A package. The Raptor 802A Luxury package adds the features of the Lariat's 502A package along with a few other features, including a 4.10 front axle with a Torsen limited-slip differential.

Many of the upper-trim features are offered on supporting models as options. Other add-ons include multiple axle ratios, off-road underbody protection, adaptive suspension dampers, and a 36-gallon fuel tank.

2. Americano: Made by diluting a shot of espresso with hot water, resulting in a strength similar to that of drip coffee but with a different flavor profile.

3. Latte: A coffee drink made with one shot of espresso and steamed milk, often topped with a small amount of foam. Flavored syrups can be added for a variety of tastes.

4. Cappuccino: Similar to a latte, but with a greater proportion of foamed milk to steamed milk, resulting in a thick layer of foam on top.

5. Macchiato: An espresso with a small amount of foamed milk on top. The name means "stained" or "spotted" in Italian, referring to the espresso being marked with milk.

6. Mocha: A latte with chocolate syrup added, usually topped with whipped cream and sometimes additional chocolate shavings or cocoa powder.

8. Iced Coffee: Brewed coffee that is cooled and served over ice, often with milk, cream, or sweetener added.

9. Frappuccino: A trademarked line of blended coffee drinks sold by Starbucks, typically made with coffee or crème base, blended with ice and other various ingredients, usually topped with whipped cream and syrups.

10. Affogato: A dessert coffee that typically takes a scoop of vanilla gelato or ice cream and "drowns" it with a shot of hot espresso.
